The '''A1081''' is a road in the south of [[England]]. It starts at [[Luton Airport]] in [[Bedfordshire]] and runs to [[Chipping Barnet|High Barnet]] in [[Greater London]] via [[Harpenden]], [[St Albans]] and [[London Colney]], a distance of around {{convert|20|mi|km}}. For most of its length, the A1081 follows the route of the original [[A6 road (England)|A6]].

==The route==
The first section of the A1081 runs south-west from Luton Airport to the spur of the [[M1 motorway]] on the southern outskirts of Luton. This section is a [[dual carriageway]] known as ''New Airport Way''. Just west of the airport, there is a junction with the [[A505 road|A505]].

At the M1 spur, the A1081 turns south to join the route of the original A6. It skirts the grounds of [[Luton Hoo]] estate, then crosses into [[Hertfordshire]], passing through Harpenden before reaching St Albans.

In St Albans, the road has a junction with the A4147 and A1057 (both making up the former [[A414 road|A414]]), then meets the [[A5183 road|A5183]] (the former [[A5 road (Great Britain)|A5]]). At this point, it bears south-east, bypassing London Colney before reaching junction 22 of the [[M25 motorway]]. There is a junction with the current A414, the ''North Orbital Road'', just north of London Colney.

The A1081 then [[Concurrency (road)|multiplexes]] with the M25 to junction 23 at [[South Mimms]], the junction with the current [[A1 road (Great Britain)|A1]] and [[A1(M) motorway|A1(M)]]. From here, it continues south-east to High Barnet, ending at a junction with the [[Great North Road (Great Britain)|Great North Road]] (the former A1, now the [[A1000 road|A1000]]).

==History==
The A1081 designation was originally used on a 1920s-built road in east London, from [[South Woodford]] to the [[A12 road (England)|A12]] at [[Gants Hill]]; this road is now part of the [[North Circular Road|A406 North Circular Road]] and the A1400.

The current A1081 was established in the 1950s, when the section of the A6 from South Mimms to High Barnet was so renumbered following the re-routing of the A1 onto the 1920s-built Barnet Bypass.

When the M25 was built in the 1980s, it took over the section of the A6 from London Colney to South Mimms, which was already dual carriageway. The section from Luton to London Colney was then renumbered the A1081.

