[[File:Kwartier van Nijmegen Frederik de Wit ca1650.jpg|thumb|400px|Nijmegen Quarter by [[Frederik de Wit]], ca 1650]]
The '''Nijmegen Quarter''' (Dutch: ''Kwartier van Nijmegen'') was the first of the four quarters in which the county, later [[duchy of Guelders]] was divided, as they were separated by rivers. In addition Guelders consisted of [[county of Zutphen|Zutphen Quarter]], the [[Upper Quarter]] and [[Veluwe Quarter]].<ref name="google">{{cite book|title=The Dutch Republic in the Seventeenth Century: The Golden Age|author1=Prak, M.|author2=Webb, D.|year=2005|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9780521843522|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JhIxrykbrKUC}}</ref> Each quarter had its own capital.
==Geography== Nijmegen Quarter, Zutphen Quarter and Veluwe Quarter are the three downstream Lower Quarters that seceded in 1581 to the [[Dutch Republic]], and constitute the present day Dutch province of [[Gelderland]]. Nijmegen Quarter with its capital at the city of [[Nijmegen]], included the area between the [[Meuse]] and [[Rhine]] with the exception of the [[Duchy of Cleves|Cleves]] [[enclave]] [[Huissen]] and the independent counties of [[County of Buren|Buren]] and [[Culemborg]], that were much later seceded to the Netherlands.<ref name="google2">{{cite book|title=In the Shadow of Burgundy: The Court of Guelders in the Late Middle Ages|author=Nijsten, G.|year=2004|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9780521820752|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RbjlEuURRKAC}}</ref> The quarter was divided in [[Nijmegen]], [[Rijk van Nijmegen]], [[Land of Maas and Waal]], the [[Bommelerwaard]] and [[Betuwe]]. The main cities were then [[Nijmegen]], [[Tiel]] and [[Zaltbommel]]. The quarter had a private university in Nijmegen.<ref name="google3">{{cite book|title=The History of Science in the Netherlands: Survey, Themes and Reference|author1=Van Berkel, K.|author2=Van Helden, A.|author3=Palm, L.C.|year=1999|publisher=Brill|isbn=9789004100060|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1jwjTsRu6AMC}}</ref>
